ce:section.ce:para:
To further explore the specific selectivity and fluorescence quenching effect of the fluorescence sensor in terms of practical applicability, the detection of MC-LR in three types of water samples was performed and validated using the standard addition method. The water samples included two types of lake water obtained from Ningyin lake and Hongze lake in South China Agricultural University and tap water collected from the laboratory. Subsequent experimental steps involved pretreatment, detection, and spiked recovery tests. The water sample was subjected to pretreatment via centrifugation at 12000 rpm for 15 min and filtration with a 0.22-μm pore size membrane thrice. Table 1
                         reveals that no MC-LR was detected in any of the three water samples. Subsequently, different concentrations of MC-LR (1, 250, and 500 μg/L) were added to the water samples to explore the spiked recoveries. The average recovery rates of MC-LR in Ningyin lake water and Hongze lake water determination ranged from 91.8% to 96.0% and 95.0% to 100.4%, respectively, while average recovery rates of MC-LR in tap water detection ranged from 94.1% to 100.7%. The results validate the practical applicability of the MIP@CQDs@SiO2 fluorescence sensor in water sample analysis. In addition, current analytical methods and products used for the determination of MC-LR in water samples were compared (Table 2
                        ). Table 2 reveals that the linear range, LOD, and incubation time in this study were comparable with those obtained in previous studies [50–54].
